TITLE.P: Services and Repair of Vehicle and Plant Lifting Equipment

SHORT_DESCR.P: Glasgow City Council main objective for this procurement exercise is to ensure that all lifting equipment is maintained in order to avoid risk to lives and property. This shall be achieved by appointing suitably qualified suppliers who shall carry out Lifting Operations and Lifting Equipment Regulations 1998 (LOLER) examination and associated repairs in accordance to manufacturer’s recommendations and with compliance with relevant legislations/regulations and best practice.

This shall include passenger tail lifts and bidders must review Document one which details all of the equipment which is covered under this agreement. Document one is available within the Buyers area in PCST.

REVIEW_PROCEDURE.P: Glasgow City Council must, by notice in writing as soon as possible after the decision has been made, inform all tenderers and candidates concerned of its decision to award the contract. The Council must allow a period of at least the relevant standstill period (where the notice is sent by facsimile or electronic means the period is 10 days ending at midnight at the end of the 10th day after that on which the last notice is sent, when sent by other means the period is 15 days) to elapse between the date of despatch of the notice referred to in Regulation 86 of The Public Contract (Scotland) Regulations 2015 (“the Regulations”). The Council is obliged to comply with the Regulations and any eligible economic operator can bring an action in the Sheriff Court or the Court of Session where as a consequence of a breach by the Council, suffers or risks suffering loss or damage. The bringing of court proceedings during the standstill period means that the Council must not enter into the contract unless the proceedings are determined, discontinued or disposed of:

— or the court, by interim order, brings to an end the prohibition. The bringing of court proceedings after the standstill period has elapsed and the remedies that are available to the courts are detailed in the Regulations. Economic operators can write to the Council seeking further clarification on the notice, to which the Council must respond within 15 days. Economic operators should be mindful to seek their own independent legal advice when they consider appropriate to do so.
